as a supersonic overdrive

40
00:01:44.333 --> 00:01:47.520
in what we're gonna cover the next hour and a half or so.

41
00:01:47.520 --> 00:01:48.540
So we're gonna start with

42
00:01:48.540 --> 00:01:50.940
an audience response question here.

43
00:01:50.940 --> 00:01:52.560
Which of the following is true concerning

44
00:01:52.560 --> 00:01:54.930
screening for depression and suicidal ideation

45
00:01:54.930 --> 00:01:56.250
in primary care?

46
00:01:56.250 --> 00:02:00.840
Does the PHQ-2 counts as a tool to screen for this?

47
00:02:00.840 --> 00:02:03.720
Depression should be delayed until at least two months

48
00:02:03.720 --> 00:02:05.460
when a woman is postpartum.

49
00:02:05.460 --> 00:02:07.320
The US Preventive Services Task Force

50
00:02:07.320 --> 00:02:09.120
recommends that all adults be screened

51
00:02:09.120 --> 00:02:11.970
for suicidal ideation in the primary care setting.

52
00:02:11.970 --> 00:02:15.030
And the task force does not recommend screening for adults

53
00:02:15.030 --> 00:02:16.683
and adolescents for depression.

54
00:02:21.840 --> 00:02:22.890
Well, this was an easy one,

55
00:02:22.890 --> 00:02:25.230
you guys are clicking on it quick.

56
00:02:25.230 --> 00:02:26.760
That's great, so yes.

57
00:02:26.760 --> 00:02:28.410
How many of you are screening for depression

58
00:02:28.410 --> 00:02:30.180
in your primary care practices?

59
00:02:30.180 --> 00:02:31.980
That's great, perfect.

60
00:02:31.980 --> 00:02:34.530
Because that is what the US Preventive Services Task Force

61
00:02:34.530 --> 00:02:37.650
wants us to do, with the Level B evidence, is regarding,

62
00:02:37.650 --> 00:02:40.170
and they require that or ask us to do that

63
00:02:40.170 --> 00:02:42.840
in adults as well as the elderly.

64
00:02:42.840 --> 00:02:45.960
And at the time was a pretty stunning recommendation

65
00:02:45.960 --> 00:02:48.900
to do this in pregnancy and in postpartum populations

66
00:02:48.900 --> 00:02:49.800
as well.

67
00:02:49.800 --> 00:02:51.390
However, what they did say

68
00:02:51.390 --> 00:02:53.490
is they did not recommend screening for,

69
00:02:53.490 --> 00:02:55.170
or insufficient evidence was available

70
00:02:55.170 --> 00:02:58.050
to screen for suicide in this patient population,

71
00:02:58.050 --> 00:02:59.700
the risks and benefits weren't quite there,

72
00:02:59.700 --> 00:03:02.370
they didn't have the data to really make a recommendation

73
00:03:02.370 --> 00:03:03.810
from that point of view.

74
00:03:03.810 --> 00:03:05.400
What they aren't able to tell us

75
00:03:05.400 --> 00:03:07.470
is what the cadence to our screening

76
00:03:07.470 --> 00:03:08.640
for depression should be,

77
00:03:08.640 --> 00:03:10.377
they didn't really comment on that.

78
00:03:10.377 --> 00:03:12.660
Are you guys doing it probably yearly

79
00:03:12.660 --> 00:03:14.670
in patient populations that don't have a history?

80
00:03:14.670 --> 00:03:15.720
That's what I've seen done,

81
00:03:15.720 --> 00:03:17.910
that's what we do in our institution.

82
00:03:17.910 --> 00:03:20.220
What about adolescents and children?

83
00:03:20.220 --> 00:03:24.780
So the USPF recommends that children, ages 12 to 18,

84
00:03:24.780 --> 00:03:27.390
be screened for depression with that level B.

85
00:03:27.390 --> 00:03:29.760
However, children younger than 12, again,

86
00:03:29.760 --> 00:03:31.080
we get the insufficient

87
00:03:31.080 --> 00:03:33.390
and we have the same insufficient rating

88
00:03:33.390 --> 00:03:36.510
for suicide screening in this population,

89
00:03:36.510 --> 00:03:39.300
which is depressing given that suicide

90
00:03:39.300 --> 00:03:41.705
is the second leading cause of death after accidents

91
00:03:41.705 --> 00:03:43.950
in childhood.

92
00:03:43.950 --> 00:03:48.120
So pretty scary stuff, wish we had a better tool to screen.

93
00:03:48.120 --> 00:03:50.020
So let's go to the next question here.

94
00:03:51.270 --> 00:03:52.470
Which of the following is true

95
00:03:52.470 --> 00:03:54.180
about major depressive disorder

96
00:03:54.180 --> 00:03:55.860
and persistent depressive disorder,

97
00:03:55.860 --> 00:03:57.870
which used to be called dysthymia?

98
00:03:57.870 --> 00:04:00.330
The depression associated with dysthymia

99
00:04:00.330 --> 00:04:03.150
is equal or as severe as that is associated

100
00:04:03.150 --> 00:04:04.800
with major depressive disorder.

101
00:04:04.800 --> 00:04:07.740
The lifetime risk is equal between men and women.

102
00:04:07.740 --> 00:04:10.527
Depression is more common in the medically ill patients.

103
00:04:10.527 --> 00:04:14.730
And dysthymic patients may have a period of a normal mood

104
00:04:14.730 --> 00:04:16.530
for at least one year during the course

105
00:04:16.530 --> 00:04:18.573
of their persistent depression.

106
00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:25.650
Looks like we got a clear favor,

107
00:04:25.650 --> 00:04:30.243
that depression is more common in medically ill patients.

108
00:04:31.650 --> 00:04:34.020
And we'll talk about how prevalent it is in a bit,

109
00:04:34.020 --> 00:04:36.090
so what is the diagnosis of major depression?

110
00:04:36.090 --> 00:04:39.420
Well, DSM-5-TR does a nice job defining it.

111
00:04:39.420 --> 00:04:42.180
It's five symptoms of depression,

112
00:04:42.180 --> 00:04:45.510
present more days than not, over a two week period of time.

113
00:04:45.510 --> 00:04:46.860
Of those five symptoms,

114
00:04:46.860 --> 00:04:49.590
one has to be either a depressed mood

115
00:04:49.590 --> 00:04:51.360
or a loss of interest in things

116
00:04:51.360 --> 00:04:53.220
that the individual used to find interesting,

117
00:04:53.220 --> 00:04:54.930
we call that anhedonia.

118
00:04:54.930 --> 00:04:56.520
And to be pathologic,

119
00:04:56.520 --> 00:05:00.210
the symptoms have to impair the individual's functioning,

120
00:05:00.210 --> 00:05:04.230
school, work, family, there's a consequence to this mood.

121
00:05:04.230 --> 00:05:07.530
We don't mean to pathologize being sad,

122
00:05:07.530 --> 00:05:08.763
this is a disorder.

123
00:05:10.560 --> 00:05:12.150
I don't remember all those criteria,

124
00:05:12.150 --> 00:05:13.110
I'll be honest with you.

125
00:05:13.110 --> 00:05:15.060
So I often go back to the SIG-E-CAPS.

126
00:05:15.060 --> 00:05:16.897
So there were eight criteria in DSM-5,

127
00:05:16.897 --> 00:05:18.720
there are seven in SIG-E-CAPS.

128
00:05:18.720 --> 00:05:20.430
The one that's missing is depression.

129
00:05:20.430 --> 00:05:22.140
I think the people that came up with with it

130
00:05:22.140 --> 00:05:23.700
assume that was a no brainer.

131
00:05:23.700 --> 00:05:25.500
But you're looking at sleep disturbances,

132
00:05:25.500 --> 00:05:26.730
too much, too little.

133
00:05:26.730 --> 00:05:29.613
A loss of interest or pleasure, that's that anhedonia.

134
00:05:29.613 --> 00:05:32.160
Then there's feelings of guilt or worthlessness

135
00:05:32.160 --> 00:05:33.750
that occurs within those two weeks.

136
00:05:33.750 --> 00:05:36.030
There can be decreased energy or fatigue.

137
00:05:36.030 --> 00:05:38.640
The concentration becomes impaired.

138
00:05:38.640 --> 00:05:41.700
Appetites change, either too much, too little, weight gain,

139
00:05:41.700 --> 00:05:43.080
weight loss, you ask about,

140
00:05:43.080 --> 00:05:45.960
and then psychomotor agitation and depression,

141
00:05:45.960 --> 00:05:48.739
as well as the dreaded suicidal ideation.

142
00:05:48.739 --> 00:05:52.140
What we'll see is when we talk about special populations,

143
00:05:52.140 --> 00:05:54.000
younger individuals, young adults,

144
00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.250
have a different presentation of symptoms

145
00:05:56.250 --> 00:05:57.930
than the older folks.

146
00:05:57.930 --> 00:05:59.881
This is a graphic representation

147
00:05:59.881 --> 00:06:01.860
of what depression can look like

148
00:06:01.860 --> 00:06:04.590
with the black bar being the normal mood state.

149
00:06:04.590 --> 00:06:07.170
You see that decrease down there

150
00:06:07.170 --> 00:06:10.560
and we'll contrast that with the dysthymia

151
00:06:10.560 --> 00:06:13.020
as well as bipolar going forward.

152
00:06:13.020 --> 00:06:14.280
So what does dysthymia,

153
00:06:14.280 --> 00:06:16.920
or the new term for that persistent depressive disorder

154
00:06:16.920 --> 00:06:17.790
look like?

155
00:06:17.790 --> 00:06:20.970
It's a depressed mood that's present for most days,

156
00:06:20.970 --> 00:06:25.050
more days than not, most of the day, more days than not,

157
00:06:25.050 --> 00:06:27.330
for at least two years.

158
00:06:27.330 --> 00:06:31.140
And during that course of time, it's the rules of two,

159
00:06:31.140 --> 00:06:33.300
the patient cannot be asymptomatic

160
00:06:33.300 --> 00:06:36.300
for greater than two consecutive months.

161
00:06:36.300 --> 00:06:38.010
In addition to being depressed,

162
00:06:38.010 --> 00:06:41.040
they have to have two additional symptoms of depression.

163
00:06:41.040 --> 00:06:42.690
So you're not at that five level,

164
00:06:42.690 --> 00:06:44.340
you're at that three level.

165
00:06:44.340 --> 00:06:46.830
So it's a more mild form of depression

166
00:06:46.830 --> 00:06:49.500
that's very chronic but is still impairing,

167
00:06:49.500 --> 00:06:51.420
it's still pathologic.

168
00:06:51.420 --> 00:06:52.290
And interestingly enough

169
00:06:52.290 --> 00:06:55.920
has the same degree or same significant level of impairment

170
00:06:55.920 --> 00:06:56.910
and adverse outcomes.

171
00:06:56.910 --> 00:06:59.190
So we really need to pay attention for this as well.

172
00:06:59.190 --> 00:07:00.540
And to give you an idea,

173
00:07:00.540 --> 00:07:04.800
the patient is hovering along that mildly depressed,

174
00:07:04.800 --> 00:07:06.390
not getting into the major depressive.

175
00:07:06.390 --> 00:07:08.790
And again, no periods of euthymia during,

176
00:07:08.790 --> 00:07:10.500
no significant periods of euthymia

177
00:07:10.500 --> 00:07:13.260
during this course of illness.

178
00:07:13.260 --> 00:07:17.310
So when we're talking about depression,

179
00:07:17.310 --> 00:07:19.620
I get the sense that there's a recognition

180
00:07:19.620 --> 00:07:21.060
of how common depression is.

181
00:07:21.060 --> 00:07:23.790
20 to 25% of women at some point in their life

182
00:07:23.790 --> 00:07:25.680
will suffer from a major depression.

183
00:07:25.680 --> 00:07:28.080
The number's closer to 10% in men.

184
00:07:28.080 --> 00:07:31.260
If you look at a community prevalence,

185
00:07:31.260 --> 00:07:34.350
it's between five and 10% at any one time.

186
00:07:34.350 --> 00:07:35.670
And then in our practices,

187
00:07:35.670 --> 00:07:38.310
in a primary care practice where we're dealing with patients

188
00:07:38.310 --> 00:07:40.320
where often comorbidity is more the rule

189
00:07:40.320 --> 00:07:42.600
or co-occurring illness is often more the rule

190
00:07:42.600 --> 00:07:43.650
than the exception,

191
00:07:43.650 --> 00:07:46.200
we see depression rates approaching 25%.

192
00:07:46.200 --> 00:07:48.390
Does that seem familiar or consistent

193
00:07:48.390 --> 00:07:50.160
with your clinical practices?

194
00:07:50.160 --> 00:07:52.920
20, 25% of patients will have a mood disturbance,

195
00:07:52.920 --> 00:07:53.910
depression.

196
00:07:53.910 --> 00:07:55.530
I don't think that's something our colleagues

197
00:07:55.530 --> 00:07:58.050
in psychiatry truly get or are categorical,

198
00:07:58.050 --> 00:08:02.730
they don't understand the complexity of the patients we see

199
00:08:02.730 --> 00:08:05.310
as well as the number of patients we see.

200
00:08:05.310 --> 00:08:09.720
Just to tease the AAFP livestream updates course,

201
00:08:09.720 --> 00:08:12.570
I'll be talking about how we can best address this issue

202
00:08:12.570 --> 00:08:14.160
in a primary care setting

203
00:08:14.160 --> 00:08:16.233
through some innovative practice models.

204
00:08:17.340 --> 00:08:18.753
Next question here.

205
00:08:20.700 --> 00:08:21.930
Which of the following is true

206
00:08:21.930 --> 00:08:23.730
about the treatments for depression?

207
00:08:23.730 --> 00:08:25.290
And we're gonna start talking about that.

208
00:08:25.290 --> 00:08:28.590
If a patient does not respond to an SSRI within two weeks,

209
00:08:28.590 --> 00:08:30.720
it's time to start another antidepressant.

210
00:08:30.720 --> 00:08:34.852
The medication of choice for patients with epilepsy

211
00:08:34.852 --> 00:08:36.150
is bupropion.

212
00:08:36.150 --> 00:08:38.730
ECT is one of the most effective treatments

213
00:08:38.730 --> 00:08:40.500
we have out there for depression.

214
00:08:40.500 --> 00:08:44.960
And antidepressants are contraindicated in patients,

215
00:08:44.960 --> 00:08:47.250
in women who are breastfeeding,

216
00:08:47.250 --> 00:08:49.100
who may have a postpartum depression.

217
00:08:54.480 --> 00:08:56.546
Yeah, everybody's getting this one right.

218
00:08:56.546 --> 00:08:58.527
Have you referred patients to ECT?

219
00:08:58.527 --> 00:09:00.990
Are you caring for patients with ECT?

220
00:09:00.990 --> 00:09:03.330
It really is an amazingly effective treatment

221
00:09:03.330 --> 00:09:05.550
that is commonly underutilized.

222
00:09:05.550 --> 00:09:07.680
One of the trends I'm gonna try to get across

223
00:09:07.680 --> 00:09:10.020
regarding depression, anxiety, bipolar,

224
00:09:10.020 --> 00:09:12.660
all sorts of things, is there a symptom?

225
00:09:12.660 --> 00:09:15.900
The disease of depression is just one potential etiology

226
00:09:15.900 --> 00:09:20.250
for somebody who's complaining of loss of interest

227
00:09:20.250 --> 00:09:24.030
or pleasure or depression or insomnia, they're a symptom.

228
00:09:24.030 --> 00:09:26.790
And any symptom really does require an evaluation.

229
00:09:26.790 --> 00:09:29.550
And there are various medications that could cause it,

230
00:09:29.550 --> 00:09:31.500
the most common or the CNS depressants

231
00:09:31.500 --> 00:09:34.980
like alcohol and sedative hypnotics like benzodiazepines

232
00:09:34.980 --> 00:09:36.810
or barbiturates.

233
00:09:36.810 --> 00:09:38.930
The centrally acting anti-hypertensives

234
00:09:38.930 --> 00:09:42.300
like reserpine, people still prescribe it,

235
00:09:42.300 --> 00:09:45.330
my grandmother was on it in the early 2000s, actually,

236
00:09:45.330 --> 00:09:46.440
it really shocked me.

237
00:09:46.440 --> 00:09:47.610
It's actually reserpine

238
00:09:47.610 --> 00:09:49.830
because it depletes monoamines in the brain,

239
00:09:49.830 --> 00:09:50.663
causes depression.

240
00:09:50.663 --> 00:09:54.210
It was one of the prototypical or theoretical basis

241
00:09:54.210 --> 00:09:56.070
for the monoamine theory of depression,

242
00:09:56.070 --> 00:09:57.420
it's very fascinating.

243
00:09:57.420 --> 00:09:59.970
And then steroids and antiepileptic medications

244
00:09:59.970 --> 00:10:00.803
are often on the list.

245
00:10:00.803 --> 00:10:03.750
But what you'll notice is not on the list are beta blockers.

246
00:10:03.750 --> 00:10:05.010
Beta blockers historically

247
00:10:05.010 --> 00:10:06.600
have been thought to cause depression,

248
00:10:06.600 --> 00:10:08.070
they can cause fatigue,

249
00:10:08.070 --> 00:10:10.880
but meta-analysis really don't suggest depression

250
00:10:10.880 --> 00:10:12.780
is a concern with them.

251
00:10:12.780 --> 00:10:14.490
We do a history and physical exam

252
00:10:14.490 --> 00:10:16.560
and we don't have a lot of evidence base

253
00:10:16.560 --> 00:10:18.720
to guide our evaluation of patients.

254
00:10:18.720 --> 00:10:21.060
But I'll tell you the first four bullet points there.

255
00:10:21.060 --> 00:10:24.600
I routinely do in my patients, BMP, CMP,

256
00:10:24.600 --> 00:10:26.700
I'm gonna check TSH if that's abnormal.

257
00:10:26.700 --> 00:10:28.770
I'll look at their free T4.

258
00:10:28.770 --> 00:10:30.390
And I live in Wisconsin,

259
00:10:30.390 --> 00:10:32.340
we have no sun for half of the year,

260
00:10:32.340 --> 00:10:34.050
so I'm gonna check a vitamin D.

261
00:10:34.050 --> 00:10:35.940
And then folate and B12 deficiency

262
00:10:35.940 --> 00:10:37.650
are associated with depression as well.

263
00:10:37.650 --> 00:10:39.600
And then the other ones are based primarily on

264
00:10:39.600 --> 00:10:42.330
individual risk factors of the patient.

265
00:10:42.330 --> 00:10:47.070
So I'm gonna frame the treatment of depression

266
00:10:47.070 --> 00:10:49.140
in these four big boxes to start with.

267
00:10:49.140 --> 00:10:51.210
One is patient education.

268
00:10:51.210 --> 00:10:53.670
We need to discuss our treatment of depression

269
00:10:53.670 --> 00:10:54.630
with the patient,

270
00:10:54.630 --> 00:10:57.720
the rationale for the choice and our recommendations,

271
00:10:57.720 --> 00:11:00.330
how long the medication's gonna take to work,

272
00:11:00.330 --> 00:11:02.640
the potential side effects of that medication.

273
00:11:02.640 --> 00:11:07.290
All are important to ensure adherence with our prescription.

274
00:11:07.290 --> 00:11:08.310
Reassurance.

275
00:11:08.310 --> 00:11:10.200
Stigma is still real.

276
00:11:10.200 --> 00:11:11.610
We have to ensure patients

277
00:11:11.610 --> 00:11:13.830
that depression is a medical disease.

278
00:11:13.830 --> 00:11:18.240
It's not a character flaw or a sign of moral weakness

279
00:11:18.240 --> 00:11:20.430
and it's a treatable disease is that.

280
00:11:20.430 --> 00:11:23.121
And then we wanna make sure that if they're willing to take

281
00:11:23.121 --> 00:11:25.500
our agreed upon course.

282
00:11:25.500 --> 00:11:27.600
We wanna make sure we're monitoring their treatment,

283
00:11:27.600 --> 00:11:30.870
not just for efficacy but also for side effects.

284
00:11:30.870 --> 00:11:33.690
We wanna be proactive in querying about side effects

285
00:11:33.690 --> 00:11:34.830
like sexual dysfunction,

286
00:11:34.830 --> 00:11:36.180
'cause patients are really hesitant

287
00:11:36.180 --> 00:11:37.470
to talk about that sort of stuff,

288
00:11:37.470 --> 00:11:39.870
and that can lead to non-adherence.

289
00:11:39.870 --> 00:11:42.000
And then if we're monitoring patients

290
00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:44.010
and they're not doing well, for goodness sake,

291
00:11:44.010 --> 00:11:47.640
let's do something about it, let's adjust our treatment.

292
00:11:47.640 --> 00:11:50.910
Because the goal is remission, not just response,

293
00:11:50.910 --> 00:11:53.973
not just better, we want them in remission.

294
00:11:54.960 --> 00:11:56.973
So how do we pick antidepressants?

295
00:11:58.170 --> 00:12:01.050
The pharma reps are gonna tell you that A is better than B,

296
00:12:01.050 --> 00:12:02.490
and A is always what they're selling,

297
00:12:02.490 --> 00:12:03.840
they're never selling B.

298
00:12:03.840 --> 00:12:06.000
But I'll tell you that for the most part,

299
00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:08.040
the antidepressants are entirely similar

300
00:12:08.040 --> 00:12:10.290
as far as an efficacy standpoint.

301
00:12:10.290 --> 00:12:11.670
So how do we choose?

302
00:12:11.670 --> 00:12:13.380
We choose first and foremost

303
00:12:13.380 --> 00:12:14.760
for what's best for the patient,

304
00:12:14.760 --> 00:12:16.530
what's safest for the patient.

305
00:12:16.530 --> 00:12:19.050
We wanna take into account their medical comorbidities

306
00:12:19.050 --> 00:12:21.090
and their psychiatric comorbidities.

307
00:12:21.090 --> 00:12:22.470
We wanna avoid medications

308
00:12:22.470 --> 00:12:25.050
that may exacerbate a medical condition

309
00:12:25.050 --> 00:12:28.980
and if ideal, we would like the two birds one stone theory.

310
00:12:28.980 --> 00:12:31.530
I have one medication that can treat a couple of problems

311
00:12:31.530 --> 00:12:33.060
that the patient has.

312
00:12:33.060 --> 00:12:35.730
We wanna avoid drug-to-drug interactions

313
00:12:35.730 --> 00:12:38.550
through pharmacokinetic and pharmacodynamic interactions,

314
00:12:38.550 --> 00:12:41.460
and we'll talk a little bit about that as we go on.

315
00:12:41.460 --> 00:12:43.710
If the medications are safe,

316
00:12:43.710 --> 00:12:45.390
then what does the patient want?

317
00:12:45.390 --> 00:12:46.470
Do they have a family member

318
00:12:46.470 --> 00:12:48.570
or a friend that's responded well to one?

319
00:12:48.570 --> 00:12:50.580
That's one they're more likely to take, right?

320
00:12:50.580 --> 00:12:52.230
It's really hard to talk a patient

321
00:12:52.230 --> 00:12:55.380
into taking a medication they don't wanna take.

322
00:12:55.380 --> 00:12:57.300
Ideally the medication they wanna take,

323
00:12:57.300 --> 00:12:58.800
they have a history of response to

324
00:12:58.800 --> 00:13:01.170
or they have a family member that's responded to.

325
00:13:01.170 --> 00:13:02.220
And last but not least,

326
00:13:02.220 --> 00:13:05.280
we consider the importance of cost

327
00:13:05.280 --> 00:13:07.980
in the medications that we're prescribing.

328
00:13:07.980 --> 00:13:11.130
Which of the following medications is avoided due to,

329
00:13:11.130 --> 00:13:12.720
which is commonly avoided

330
00:13:12.720 --> 00:13:14.687
due to potentially life-threatening side effects?

331
00:13:14.687 --> 00:13:18.300
SSRIs, monoamine oxidase inhibitors,

332
00:13:18.300 --> 00:13:22.623
serotonin modulators or norepinephrine reuptake inhibitors?

333
00:13:28.800 --> 00:13:31.350
Yeah, I'm making these too easy for you.

334
00:13:31.350 --> 00:13:34.415
Have any of you ever prescribed a monoamine ox inhibitor?

335
00:13:34.415 --> 00:13:35.850
Got one person.

336
00:13:35.850 --> 00:13:37.740
Has anybody followed a patient with a mono?

337
00:13:37.740 --> 00:13:38.880
That's impressive.

338
00:13:38.880 --> 00:13:40.260
I have never prescribed a mono,

339
00:13:40.260 --> 00:13:43.530
I've been doing this for 30 years, I never prescribed one.

340
00:13:43.530 --> 00:13:45.540
We're gonna break down the antidepressants

341
00:13:45.540 --> 00:13:48.913
in two big cohorts, first generation and second generation,

342
00:13:48.913 --> 00:13:52.200
and they're broken by side effects.

343
00:13:52.200 --> 00:13:55.110
These are the pharmacodynamic interactions

344
00:13:55.110 --> 00:13:57.210
I was talking about a couple of slides before.

345
00:13:57.210 --> 00:13:58.710
These are predictable side effects.

346
00:13:58.710 --> 00:14:01.440
If I give you a medication that impacts serotonin,

347
00:14:01.440 --> 00:14:05.310
I can educate the patient about potential side effects.

348
00:14:05.310 --> 00:14:08.490
So serotonin, norepinephrine and dopamine,

349
00:14:08.490 --> 00:14:11.040
they're we think important for the treatment response

350
00:14:11.040 --> 00:14:11.940
of an antidepressant,

351
00:14:11.940 --> 00:14:13.530
but they're associated with side effects.

352
00:14:13.530 --> 00:14:16.350
Serotonin causes sexual dysfunction,

353
00:14:16.350 --> 00:14:18.810
it can cause GI disturbance, increased bleeding risks,

354
00:14:18.810 --> 00:14:20.190
and it can lead to toxicity

355
00:14:20.190 --> 00:14:21.897
if combined with other serotonergic medications,

356
00:14:21.897 --> 00:14:23.940
and you get serotonin toxicity,

357
00:14:23.940 --> 00:14:25.830
also called serotonin syndrome.

358
00:14:25.830 --> 00:14:27.840
Norepinephrine, great for depression

359
00:14:27.840 --> 00:14:30.630
but can cause anxiety, arousal, insomnia,

360
00:14:30.630 --> 00:14:32.550
and even autonomic arousal.

361
00:14:32.550 --> 00:14:36.870
Dopamine, nausea, sometimes psychosis and some activation.

362
00:14:36.870 --> 00:14:39.030
The other neurotransmitters here

363
00:14:39.030 --> 00:14:41.130
are primarily nuisance side effects,

364
00:14:41.130 --> 00:14:44.700
with orthostasis, not necessarily a nuisance side effect.

365
00:14:44.700 --> 00:14:48.543
if an older person gets orthostatic falls and breaks a hip.

366
00:14:49.380 --> 00:14:51.570
They also have anticholinergic side effects

367
00:14:51.570 --> 00:14:53.364
that we wanna really avoid in the elderly.

368
00:14:53.364 --> 00:14:58.364
That's cognitive, that's constipation, urinary retention,

369
00:14:59.460 --> 00:15:01.890
dry mouth, cognitive issues.

370
00:15:01.890 --> 00:15:03.960
And then histamine and sedation and weight gain,

371
00:15:03.960 --> 00:15:06.330
which can be a negative side effect in some patients

372
00:15:06.330 --> 00:15:09.000
if they're obese already or at risk of diabetes.

373
00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:11.040
But if they're cachectic and medically ill,

374
00:15:11.040 --> 00:15:13.200
can be a benefit, and if they're not sleeping well,

375
00:15:13.200 --> 00:15:15.030
so we'll talk a little bit about that.

376
00:15:15.030 --> 00:15:17.487
The first generations we don't commonly use for depression

377
00:15:17.487 --> 00:15:20.100
are the monoamines and the tricyclics.

378
00:15:20.100 --> 00:15:21.750
The monoamines,

379
00:15:21.750 --> 00:15:24.120
they prevent the breakdown of the the monoamines

380
00:15:24.120 --> 00:15:26.430
in the synaptic cleft, hence their name.

381
00:15:26.430 --> 00:15:29.160
They're associated, that life-threatening risk,

382
00:15:29.160 --> 00:15:30.990
is due to drug-to-drug interactions.

383
00:15:30.990 --> 00:15:33.120
But also due to the tyramine diet

384
00:15:33.120 --> 00:15:34.830
that these patients have to follow.

385
00:15:34.830 --> 00:15:38.670
They have to avoid aged cheese, processed meats,

386
00:15:38.670 --> 00:15:42.990
smoked meats, draft beer, not a Wisconsin friendly diet.

387
00:15:42.990 --> 00:15:44.700
That's one of the reasons we never prescribe it

388
00:15:44.700 --> 00:15:46.080
in Wisconsin.

389
00:15:46.080 --> 00:15:49.170
But it can be dangerous if they don't follow that diet

390
00:15:49.170 --> 00:15:50.760
or if they take another medication

391
00:15:50.760 --> 00:15:53.913
that may impact serotonin, risk of serotonin syndrome.

392
00:15:54.810 --> 00:15:56.742
The tricyclic antidepressants

393
00:15:56.742 --> 00:16:00.480
were one of the first antidepressants because,

394
00:16:00.480 --> 00:16:03.360
well, actually they were originally used as antihistamines,

395
00:16:03.360 --> 00:16:05.970
they have very potent antihistaminergic properties.

396
00:16:05.970 --> 00:16:07.320
But they discovered that these patients

397
00:16:07.320 --> 00:16:09.270
were no longer sneezing, they didn't have a runny nose

398
00:16:09.270 --> 00:16:10.410
and they weren't depressed anymore.

399
00:16:10.410 --> 00:16:12.870
So they went down the line of depression.

400
00:16:12.870 --> 00:16:15.219
It has a lot of pharmacotherapy properties.

401
00:16:15.219 --> 00:16:18.570
Some are good, the serotonin and the norepinephrine,

402
00:16:18.570 --> 00:16:19.860
some are bad.

403
00:16:19.860 --> 00:16:23.520
The anticholinergic impact, the alpha antagonism,

404
00:16:23.520 --> 00:16:24.780
causing falls.

405
00:16:24.780 --> 00:16:29.520
And I'm really glad I never was practicing too much

406
00:16:29.520 --> 00:16:32.430
where TCAs were a primary treatment

407
00:16:32.430 --> 00:16:34.260
because of that one at six o'clock,

408
00:16:34.260 --> 00:16:36.300
the blockade of the sodium channels.

409
00:16:36.300 --> 00:16:38.940
That's why these medications are lethal in overdoses.

410
00:16:38.940 --> 00:16:40.846
So one week supply of an antidepressant

411
00:16:40.846 --> 00:16:45.330
is lethal in overdose, not a great antidepressant,

412
00:16:45.330 --> 00:16:46.500
from a safety standpoint.

413
00:16:46.500 --> 00:16:48.930
Good antidepressant, not just that great.

414
00:16:48.930 --> 00:16:51.813
So we use the second generations every chance we get,

415
00:16:52.740 --> 00:16:54.090
and we'll talk a little bit about those.

416
00:16:54.090 --> 00:16:55.950
The serotonin reuptake inhibitors,

417
00:16:55.950 --> 00:16:59.370
primarily inhibit the reuptake of serotonin,

418
00:16:59.370 --> 00:17:01.800
so are associated with those serotonin side effects,

419
00:17:01.800 --> 00:17:06.510
of GI upset, increased risk of bleeding, sexual dysfunction.

420
00:17:06.510 --> 00:17:09.660
There are five for depression, I draw that black line.

421
00:17:09.660 --> 00:17:11.700
I usually prescribe the top three,

422
00:17:11.700 --> 00:17:13.890
I very rarely prescribe the bottom two.

423
00:17:13.890 --> 00:17:17.340
The last speaker mentioned the QT concerns with citalopram.

424
00:17:17.340 --> 00:17:19.140
Paroxetine I tend not to use

425
00:17:19.140 --> 00:17:20.670
'cause it has a very short half-life.

426
00:17:20.670 --> 00:17:21.660
People forget a dose,

427
00:17:21.660 --> 00:17:23.340
they go through discontinuation syndrome

428
00:17:23.340 --> 00:17:24.600
and they're not happy.

429
00:17:24.600 --> 00:17:26.790
It also has a lot of drug-to-drug interactions

430
00:17:26.790 --> 00:17:28.170
and is anticholinergic.

431
00:17:28.170 --> 00:17:31.380
So I tend to avoid it for all of those reasons.

432
00:17:31.380 --> 00:17:34.135
We go to the SNRIs, they're serotonin reuptake inhibitors,

433
00:17:34.135 --> 00:17:35.610
so we have those side effects,

434
00:17:35.610 --> 00:17:37.230
but now we have norepinephrine pushed in,

435
00:17:37.230 --> 00:17:38.580
which can be beneficial

436
00:17:38.580 --> 00:17:40.710
but is associated with its own problems

437
00:17:40.710 --> 00:17:45.423
of autonomic arousal, anxiety and those kind of things.

438
00:17:46.475 --> 00:17:49.290
So the same black line, I tend to use the ones above it,

439
00:17:49.290 --> 00:17:51.210
and tend not to use the ones below it.

440
00:17:51.210 --> 00:17:52.380
One of the important things

441
00:17:52.380 --> 00:17:54.870
is they may all be classified as SNRIs

442
00:17:54.870 --> 00:17:56.130
but they have different activity

443
00:17:56.130 --> 00:17:58.170
at serotonin and norepinephrine.

444
00:17:58.170 --> 00:18:01.350
Venlafaxine is just a really expensive SSRI

445
00:18:01.350 --> 00:18:03.750
until you get past 100 milligrams.

446
00:18:03.750 --> 00:18:06.270
Then the norepinephrine reuptake kicks in.

447
00:18:06.270 --> 00:18:10.230
Duloxetine, pretty much equal across the dose range.

448
00:18:10.230 --> 00:18:13.170
And then you have the one down there, Levomilnacipran,

449
00:18:13.170 --> 00:18:15.000
is more norepinephrine than serotonin

450
00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:16.473
across the dose ranges.

451
00:18:17.310 --> 00:18:18.480
The unique one here,

452
00:18:18.480 --> 00:18:20.040
I'm sure you're all very familiar with,

453
00:18:20.040 --> 00:18:22.680
is the FDA indications for neuropathic pain

454
00:18:22.680 --> 00:18:25.530
and chronic pain with duloxetine, which is a nice thing.

455
00:18:25.530 --> 00:18:28.230
Norepinephrine and dopamine reuptake inhibitor

456
00:18:28.230 --> 00:18:30.660
is what bupropion is.

457
00:18:30.660 --> 00:18:34.020
And therefore it doesn't cause sexual dysfunction,

458
00:18:34.020 --> 00:18:36.030
it doesn't cause weight gain,

459
00:18:36.030 --> 00:18:38.580
but it does have a concern of seizures.

460
00:18:38.580 --> 00:18:41.460
Initially, when we were using the old IR formulation

461
00:18:41.460 --> 00:18:43.170
that required three times a day dosing,

462
00:18:43.170 --> 00:18:45.150
you'd see a spike in the serum levels,

463
00:18:45.150 --> 00:18:48.180
that was associated with the lowering of seizure threshold,

464
00:18:48.180 --> 00:18:50.400
but it still carries that as a risk factor.

465
00:18:50.400 --> 00:18:52.080
So we tend to avoid it at patients

466
00:18:52.080 --> 00:18:54.600
with a history of seizures or at risk of seizures.

467
00:18:54.600 --> 00:18:56.670
And also eating disorder patients

468
00:18:56.670 --> 00:18:59.430
because they get a lot of electrolyte abnormalities,

469
00:18:59.430 --> 00:19:02.970
which may also predispose them to seizures.

470
00:19:02.970 --> 00:19:04.260
But a lot of benefits there

471
00:19:04.260 --> 00:19:06.930
as far as weight gain and lack of sexual dysfunction.

472
00:19:06.930 --> 00:19:09.330
Mirtazapine increases serotonin

473
00:19:09.330 --> 00:19:10.440
through a different mechanism.

474
00:19:10.440 --> 00:19:13.230
It's through the Alpha-2 antagonism,

475
00:19:13.230 --> 00:19:15.540
but it has a couple of really unique other factors.

476
00:19:15.540 --> 00:19:18.240
It's antihistaminergic so it increases weight gain

477
00:19:18.240 --> 00:19:19.830
and is fairly sedating.

478
00:19:19.830 --> 00:19:22.980
So it can be helpful for the cachectic insomnia patient

479
00:19:22.980 --> 00:19:25.800
that when I round in the hospital on a consult service

480
00:19:25.800 --> 00:19:27.630
is really, really common.

481
00:19:27.630 --> 00:19:30.780
It also blocks various serotonin receptors

482
00:19:30.780 --> 00:19:33.540
and one that it blocks is 5HT3.

483
00:19:33.540 --> 00:19:37.350
What other medication blocks 5HT3 that we use all the time?

484
00:19:37.350 --> 00:19:39.690
Zofran, ondansetron.

485
00:19:39.690 --> 00:19:42.750
So this also can help prevent some nausea.

486
00:19:42.750 --> 00:19:44.850
So we use this like water

487
00:19:44.850 --> 00:19:47.640
when we're rounding on the oncology service on consults,

488
00:19:47.640 --> 00:19:50.035
not sleeping, not eating, nauseated all the time

489
00:19:50.035 --> 00:19:51.270
and depressed.

490
00:19:51.270 --> 00:19:54.090
It's a good medication for those patients.

491
00:19:54.090 --> 00:19:57.060
These are some of the newer ones, the serotonin modulators.

492
00:19:57.060 --> 00:20:00.183
The serotonin modulators are all re-uptake inhibitors,

493
00:20:02.040 --> 00:20:04.680
but they have different addition to serotonin receptors,

494
00:20:04.680 --> 00:20:07.350
agonism, partial agonism and antagonism.

495
00:20:07.350 --> 00:20:09.390
We really don't know what those add.

496
00:20:09.390 --> 00:20:11.730
They have less weight gain and less sexual side effects

497
00:20:11.730 --> 00:20:12.630
and we'll take it at that,

498
00:20:12.630 --> 00:20:14.490
but they're the same antidepressant properties.

499
00:20:14.490 --> 00:20:15.783
Same with Vilazodone.

500
00:20:16.830 --> 00:20:20.550
SSRI with a partial agonism at 5HT1.

501
00:20:20.550 --> 00:20:24.000
Good for depression with less sexual side effects.

502
00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:26.212
The one thing I will say about the two serotonin modulators

503
00:20:26.212 --> 00:20:29.490
on the bottom is they're associated with a lot of nausea.

504
00:20:29.490 --> 00:20:32.370
So you start low and inch your way up

505
00:20:32.370 --> 00:20:34.353
or patients just do not like it.

506
00:20:35.820 --> 00:20:38.010
These are two new ones that I just want to talk about

507
00:20:38.010 --> 00:20:39.780
'cause you have some pharma reps coming to you.

508
00:20:39.780 --> 00:20:41.013
The first one is Gepirone.

509
00:20:41.013 --> 00:20:42.300
Have you guys heard about that?

510
00:20:42.300 --> 00:20:44.250
Has anybody come to talk to you about that?

511
00:20:44.250 --> 00:20:46.830
This medication has been around for 40 years

512
00:20:46.830 --> 00:20:48.180
and pharma has been trying to get it approved

513
00:20:48.180 --> 00:20:50.310
for major depression for 40 years,

514
00:20:50.310 --> 00:20:51.810
but it's been turned down.

515
00:20:51.810 --> 00:20:55.530
I don't know how they did it, they finally got it approved.

516
00:20:55.530 --> 00:20:57.420
It probably brings nothing,

517
00:20:57.420 --> 00:21:01.230
it's probably a very mediocre antidepressant if that.

518
00:21:01.230 --> 00:21:02.450
Really the only role I can think of

519
00:21:02.450 --> 00:21:04.590
is it has no sexual side effects.

520
00:21:04.590 --> 00:21:06.210
So it may be appropriate for the patients

521
00:21:06.210 --> 00:21:09.690
that can't tolerate anything else, but have that.

522
00:21:09.690 --> 00:21:10.740
This is the other new one.

523
00:21:10.740 --> 00:21:12.150
This is an interesting mechanism,

524
00:21:12.150 --> 00:21:14.730
it's a combination of dextromethorphan, yes,

525
00:21:14.730 --> 00:21:17.430
just dextromethorphan and bupropion.

526
00:21:17.430 --> 00:21:22.050
The bupropion, it's unique in that the dextromethorphan,

527
00:21:22.050 --> 00:21:24.240
so it has the dopamine, it has the norepinephrine,

528
00:21:24.240 --> 00:21:26.520
but now we bring another neurotransmitter, glutamate,

529
00:21:26.520 --> 00:21:29.610
into the picture through dextromethorphan.

530
00:21:29.610 --> 00:21:32.190
So it has that antidepressant property as well.

531
00:21:32.190 --> 00:21:35.400
What's unique about this medication is it may work faster.

532
00:21:35.400 --> 00:21:36.780
There's some evidence that it can work

533
00:21:36.780 --> 00:21:38.880
within a week to two weeks.

534
00:21:38.880 --> 00:21:41.730
So maybe that glutamate brings something to the picture.

535
00:21:41.730 --> 00:21:42.600
Very fascinating.

536
00:21:42.600 --> 00:21:44.190
The bupropion is actually added

537
00:21:44.190 --> 00:21:47.940
because it inhibits the metabolism of dextromethorphan,

538
00:21:47.940 --> 00:21:50.640
and extends its half life to about a day.

539
00:21:50.640 --> 00:21:53.070
Also it's an antidepressant as well.

540
00:21:53.070 --> 00:21:54.150
But it's interesting.

541
00:21:54.150 --> 00:21:55.650
So the American College of Physicians

542
00:21:55.650 --> 00:21:57.660
has a couple of general statements here.

543
00:21:57.660 --> 00:21:59.970
Recommendation one in how we approach depression

544
00:21:59.970 --> 00:22:02.550
is moderate or severe depression

545
00:22:02.550 --> 00:22:05.520
can be treated through either evidence-based psychotherapy,

546
00:22:05.520 --> 00:22:08.010
primarily CBT, that's almost always the answer

547
00:22:08.010 --> 00:22:11.850
on a board exam, is CBT when psychotherapy comes in.

548
00:22:11.850 --> 00:22:14.720
Or through a combination of both CBT

549
00:22:14.720 --> 00:22:17.160
and psycho-pharmacology.

550
00:22:17.160 --> 00:22:21.390
Mild depression, primary treatment should be

551
00:22:21.390 --> 00:22:23.615
evidence-based cognitive behavioral therapy.

552
00:22:23.615 --> 00:22:28.615
So you have monotherapy for severe, moderate-severe

553
00:22:28.950 --> 00:22:30.570
or combination therapy,

554
00:22:30.570 --> 00:22:33.780
and then for mild you're looking at CBT.

555
00:22:33.780 --> 00:22:36.750
But as I mentioned, we wanna monitor patient's outcomes.

556
00:22:36.750 --> 00:22:37.957
We use the same score,

557
00:22:37.957 --> 00:22:40.299
the same scale we did for the diagnosis

558
00:22:40.299 --> 00:22:41.700
or the screening of depression.

559
00:22:41.700 --> 00:22:44.340
We can use to follow somebody's response

560
00:22:44.340 --> 00:22:47.490
with the goal of that being less than five remission.

561
00:22:47.490 --> 00:22:50.430
We wanna get them to response, half their prior score,

562
00:22:50.430 --> 00:22:52.410
and move them towards remission.

563
00:22:52.410 --> 00:22:55.080
How do we do that? Not always easy to do.

564
00:22:55.080 --> 00:22:56.367
If we prescribe a medication,

565
00:22:56.367 --> 00:22:59.250
we visit the patient in four to six weeks,

566
00:22:59.250 --> 00:23:01.410
not working, we wanna look at a couple things.

567
00:23:01.410 --> 00:23:04.710
One, did I get the diagnosis right?

568
00:23:04.710 --> 00:23:07.860
Two, are they taking the medications that are prescribed?

569
00:23:07.860 --> 00:23:10.950
Three, do I have the dose as high as I can reasonably,

570
00:23:10.950 --> 00:23:13.470
as high as I can get it that they can tolerate it?

571
00:23:13.470 --> 00:23:15.360
If the answers are all yes to those, you look,

572
00:23:15.360 --> 00:23:17.940
did they have any response to the antidepressant?

573
00:23:17.940 --> 00:23:20.820
If they did, but I just can't get 'em over the hump,

574
00:23:20.820 --> 00:23:22.080
maybe then augmenting,

575
00:23:22.080 --> 00:23:23.880
adding another medication is the answer.

576
00:23:23.880 --> 00:23:26.040
If they really haven't had any response,

577
00:23:26.040 --> 00:23:29.010
then it may be time to consider switching.

578
00:23:29.010 --> 00:23:31.770
So how do you do that? That's recommendation three here,

579
00:23:31.770 --> 00:23:33.810
is you can consider switching to

580
00:23:33.810 --> 00:23:35.850
or augmenting the existing treatment

581
00:23:35.850 --> 00:23:37.590
with cognitive behavioral therapy

582
00:23:37.590 --> 00:23:39.240
or you can switch to a different

583
00:23:39.240 --> 00:23:40.830
second generation antidepressant

584
00:23:40.830 --> 00:23:42.870
or augment with an entirely different type

585
00:23:42.870 --> 00:23:47.280
of psychiatric medication, we'll talk about in a bit here.

586
00:23:47.280 --> 00:23:49.290
So this is what the treatment of depression

587
00:23:49.290 --> 00:23:50.520
should look like.

588
00:23:50.520 --> 00:23:53.010
You get somebody down, you initiate treatment,

589
00:23:53.010 --> 00:23:55.110
and then the goal is to get them into that remission

590
00:23:55.110 --> 00:23:56.520
back at euthymic.

591
00:23:56.520 --> 00:24:00.270
And then, important, is you have a continuation phase.

592
00:24:00.270 --> 00:24:02.430
The average length of a depression episode

593
00:24:02.430 --> 00:24:05.610
is about four to six months, natural history.

594
00:24:05.610 --> 00:24:07.500
So we'd use this continuity phase

595
00:24:07.500 --> 00:24:10.050
to treat them through that episode.

596
00:24:10.050 --> 00:24:12.360
Then some patients need ongoing maintenance,

597
00:24:12.360 --> 00:24:13.980
potentially for the rest of their life.

598
00:24:13.980 --> 00:24:16.950
Those are patients that had a really bad first episode

599
00:24:16.950 --> 00:24:19.350
or the key, often on tests,

600
00:24:19.350 --> 00:24:21.570
are they've had three or more episodes of depression.

601
00:24:21.570 --> 00:24:23.490
Those are the patients that are likely

602
00:24:23.490 --> 00:24:25.140
to have a fourth, fifth, and sixth,

603
00:24:25.140 --> 00:24:27.450
so we'd like to prevent that by maintenance therapy.

604
00:24:27.450 --> 00:24:29.250
The good news, it's the antidepressant dose

605
00:24:29.250 --> 00:24:32.580
that worked to get them over is what you continue.

606
00:24:32.580 --> 00:24:34.258
So as far as augmentation,

607
00:24:34.258 --> 00:24:36.810
we talk that we can add psychotherapy,

608
00:24:36.810 --> 00:24:39.450
we can also add these kind of medications to the mix,

609
00:24:39.450 --> 00:24:42.009
various antipsychotics, atypical antipsychotics.

610
00:24:42.009 --> 00:24:44.460
We have six out there that have been approved

611
00:24:44.460 --> 00:24:47.370
to augment non-patients who have had a partial response

612
00:24:47.370 --> 00:24:48.300
to antidepressants.

613
00:24:48.300 --> 00:24:51.600
So you leave them on the antidepressant and you add those.

614
00:24:51.600 --> 00:24:53.310
The two that I use most commonly

615
00:24:53.310 --> 00:24:55.680
are aripiprazole and brexpiprazole.

616
00:24:55.680 --> 00:24:57.870
Sometimes I'll refer to a specialty clinic

617
00:24:57.870 --> 00:25:00.930
for Esketamine or I'll add an antidepressant

618
00:25:00.930 --> 00:25:01.860
from a different class.

619
00:25:01.860 --> 00:25:03.300
So if they're on an SSRI,

620
00:25:03.300 --> 00:25:07.113
I may add mirtazapine or bupropion to the mix.

621
00:25:08.220 --> 00:25:09.450
If that doesn't work,

622
00:25:09.450 --> 00:25:11.220
then you get a little bit more experimental.

623
00:25:11.220 --> 00:25:12.960
And depending on your comfort level,

624
00:25:12.960 --> 00:25:16.290
you may want to add quetiapine, add lithium.

625
00:25:16.290 --> 00:25:20.310
There's some evidence that T3 works, SAM-e i folate.

626
00:25:20.310 --> 00:25:21.450
But usually these patients

627
00:25:21.450 --> 00:25:23.400
should end up going to a psychiatric consultant

628
00:25:23.400 --> 00:25:24.840
'cause we'll consider a number of things

629
00:25:24.840 --> 00:25:27.663
including that ECT given its effectiveness.

630
00:25:28.620 --> 00:25:30.810
Patients have a lot of concern about the memory problems,

631
00:25:30.810 --> 00:25:32.310
they're usually very short term

632
00:25:32.310 --> 00:25:35.970
and tend to resolve as time progresses,

633
00:25:35.970 --> 00:25:37.950
RTMS and then ketamine.

634
00:25:37.950 --> 00:25:39.300
You have all those ketamine clinics

635
00:25:39.300 --> 00:25:40.950
kind of springing up where you're practicing,

636
00:25:40.950 --> 00:25:43.350
the billboards, come to us.

637
00:25:43.350 --> 00:25:46.200
Usually they're run by anesthesiologists, not psychiatrists,

638
00:25:46.200 --> 00:25:49.980
so take those ketamine clinics with a grain of salt.

639
00:25:49.980 --> 00:25:52.050
Let's switch to the different patient populations

640
00:25:52.050 --> 00:25:54.900
for the next five or six minutes here.

641
00:25:54.900 --> 00:25:56.704
So geriatric depression,

642
00:25:56.704 --> 00:25:59.610
a little bit more common than the patient and the adult.

643
00:25:59.610 --> 00:26:02.370
As medical illnesses progress, as they become more severe,

644
00:26:02.370 --> 00:26:04.230
you see increasing rates of depression.

645
00:26:04.230 --> 00:26:07.380
Some suggest that geriatric depression can be up to 50%

646
00:26:07.380 --> 00:26:09.587
and it's unfortunately not commonly diagnosed

647
00:26:09.587 --> 00:26:12.090
when present in primary care settings.

648
00:26:12.090 --> 00:26:13.350
The good news is the PHQ-nine

649
00:26:13.350 --> 00:26:15.780
works for this population as well.

650
00:26:15.780 --> 00:26:19.890
They're commonly comorbid with anxiety disorders.

651
00:26:19.890 --> 00:26:21.930
But depression is also quite comorbid

652
00:26:21.930 --> 00:26:24.270
with dementia, neurocognitive deficits

653
00:26:24.270 --> 00:26:26.310
and actually leads to more nursing home placements

654
00:26:26.310 --> 00:26:27.630
and things like that.

655
00:26:27.630 --> 00:26:30.840
And unfortunately, the elderly are overrepresented

656
00:26:30.840 --> 00:26:35.640
in completed suicides, they represent 12% of the population,

657
00:26:35.640 --> 00:26:39.120
but almost double that, 25%, over double that,

658
00:26:39.120 --> 00:26:41.850
25% of completed suicides.

659
00:26:41.850 --> 00:26:43.080
Very sad.

660
00:26:43.080 --> 00:26:45.510
They usually use more lethal means i.e guns,

661
00:26:45.510 --> 00:26:47.310
and don't have the biological reserve

662
00:26:47.310 --> 00:26:49.260
to recover as well as the younger.

663
00:26:49.260 --> 00:26:51.721
I alluded to the fact that elderly and younger folks

664
00:26:51.721 --> 00:26:53.160
have different depression.

665
00:26:53.160 --> 00:26:56.010
The elderly have a very somatic type of depression.

666
00:26:56.010 --> 00:26:58.680
They usually don't come presenting with depression,

667
00:26:58.680 --> 00:27:00.210
I'm feeling sad or tearful.

668
00:27:00.210 --> 00:27:01.890
It's I've lost interest in doing things

669
00:27:01.890 --> 00:27:05.100
and I'm not sleeping and I have no energy.

670
00:27:05.100 --> 00:27:06.900
They both have suicidal ideation.

671
00:27:06.900 --> 00:27:11.900
They both can feel guilt and things like that.

672
00:27:13.080 --> 00:27:15.630
But primarily the elderly

673
00:27:15.630 --> 00:27:19.110
are more somatically preoccupied when they get depressed.

674
00:27:19.110 --> 00:27:21.270
That leads to this concept of pseudo-dementia.

675
00:27:21.270 --> 00:27:23.040
We usually don't use that term anymore,

676
00:27:23.040 --> 00:27:25.050
it's called dementia of depression.

677
00:27:25.050 --> 00:27:27.333
It's the idea that when patients are depressed,

678
00:27:27.333 --> 00:27:30.360
they often will complain of cognitive deficits,

679
00:27:30.360 --> 00:27:33.000
if the depression is treated, the depression lifts,

680
00:27:33.000 --> 00:27:35.250
the cognitive issues resolve.

681
00:27:35.250 --> 00:27:37.110
We'll tell you that most of these patients

682
00:27:37.110 --> 00:27:41.370
with dementia of depression will go on to develop dementia

683
00:27:41.370 --> 00:27:43.173
if you follow them longitudinally.

684
00:27:44.010 --> 00:27:45.720
One of the key tricks of the trade

685
00:27:45.720 --> 00:27:47.940
is patients with dementia itself

686
00:27:47.940 --> 00:27:50.280
usually don't complain about the memory loss,

687
00:27:50.280 --> 00:27:51.450
it's their family.

688
00:27:51.450 --> 00:27:53.550
Whereas patients with dementia of depression

689
00:27:53.550 --> 00:27:57.870
let you know about their cognitive issues all of the time.

690
00:27:57.870 --> 00:28:00.060
So that's one of the tricks of the trade.

691
00:28:00.060 --> 00:28:03.090
And potentially one of the serotonin modulators,

692
00:28:03.090 --> 00:28:06.030
Vortioxetine, has been shown to improve

693
00:28:06.030 --> 00:28:08.018
cognitive functioning in patients with depression,

694
00:28:08.018 --> 00:28:10.710
so it may have a unique role there.

695
00:28:10.710 --> 00:28:12.870
Elderly patients suffer psychotic depression

696
00:28:12.870 --> 00:28:14.310
more than non-elderly.

697
00:28:14.310 --> 00:28:17.100
And when they suffered, it's not the hallucinations type,

698
00:28:17.100 --> 00:28:18.780
it's the nihilistic delusions.

699
00:28:18.780 --> 00:28:22.080
They have pessimistic delusions about death,

700
00:28:22.080 --> 00:28:24.780
dying and disease, and often very somatic.

701
00:28:24.780 --> 00:28:27.360
And psychotic depression is not managed

702
00:28:27.360 --> 00:28:28.740
only by an antidepressant,

703
00:28:28.740 --> 00:28:31.710
you have to add an antipsychotic often to the mix.

704
00:28:31.710 --> 00:28:34.290
And then ECT is amazingly effective,

705
00:28:34.290 --> 00:28:35.910
with one or two ECTs,

706
00:28:35.910 --> 00:28:39.150
you can resolve a psychotic depression

707
00:28:39.150 --> 00:28:41.373
much faster than you can with psychopharm.

708
00:28:42.930 --> 00:28:44.940
If we just are dealing with regular depression,

709
00:28:44.940 --> 00:28:48.450
it's an SSRI is first line, start low, go slow,

710
00:28:48.450 --> 00:28:51.120
well tolerated, dependence doesn't develop,

711
00:28:51.120 --> 00:28:53.460
but don't minimize the other antidepressants

712
00:28:53.460 --> 00:28:54.375
in your armamentarium.

713
00:28:54.375 --> 00:28:58.590
The SNRIs, bupropion can work as well as again,

714
00:28:58.590 --> 00:29:01.200
mirtazapine for those cachectic, nauseated,

715
00:29:01.200 --> 00:29:03.333
not sleeping patients that are anxious.

716
00:29:04.260 --> 00:29:05.730
So pediatric patients,

717
00:29:05.730 --> 00:29:07.920
I'm pretty comfortable with the SSRIs.

718
00:29:07.920 --> 00:29:11.460
The FDA has approved fluoxetine and escitalopram.

719
00:29:11.460 --> 00:29:14.460
I tend to stay away from other pharmacotherapies,

720
00:29:14.460 --> 00:29:16.710
I don't wanna minimize the importance of therapy,

721
00:29:16.710 --> 00:29:19.020
CBT in this patient populations.

722
00:29:19.020 --> 00:29:23.010
Antidepressants are not contraindicated in lactation,

723
00:29:23.010 --> 00:29:25.140
they're very appropriate in lactation.

724
00:29:25.140 --> 00:29:26.970
If families are very concerned,

725
00:29:26.970 --> 00:29:28.650
you can get an infant level tested

726
00:29:28.650 --> 00:29:31.170
for a level to show it's non-detectable.

727
00:29:31.170 --> 00:29:33.540
Which of the following is true for postpartum depression?

728
00:29:33.540 --> 00:29:35.760
Baby blues typically resolve spontaneously

729
00:29:35.760 --> 00:29:37.680
at the eighth week postpartum.

730
00:29:37.680 --> 00:29:40.680
Patients are predisposed by a prior history of depression.

731
00:29:40.680 --> 00:29:42.810
Therapy is more effective than medications

732
00:29:42.810 --> 00:29:44.640
for moderate to severe PPD.

733
00:29:44.640 --> 00:29:46.182
Or antidepressant discontinuation

734
00:29:46.182 --> 00:29:49.923
does not increase the risk of subsequent PPD.

735
00:29:55.230 --> 00:29:57.450
All right, you guys are getting that done.

736
00:29:57.450 --> 00:29:58.283
Good.

737
00:29:58.283 --> 00:30:02.520
So a pregnancy is not protected for depression.

738
00:30:02.520 --> 00:30:04.890
The same 15% of women that were depressed

739
00:30:04.890 --> 00:30:06.750
in the general population before,

740
00:30:06.750 --> 00:30:08.820
go on to be depressed during peripartum,

741
00:30:08.820 --> 00:30:10.800
during their pregnancy and postpartum.

742
00:30:10.800 --> 00:30:14.220
Baby blues is not pathologic, it's amazingly common,

743
00:30:14.220 --> 00:30:16.980
it's onset with is in 48 to 72 hours

744
00:30:16.980 --> 00:30:20.280
and it is self-limited by two weeks, it's usually gone.

745
00:30:20.280 --> 00:30:23.070
Support, the treatment is support,

746
00:30:23.070 --> 00:30:24.570
encourage family members to be there,

747
00:30:24.570 --> 00:30:27.829
encourage the woman to ask for support as much as possible.

748
00:30:27.829 --> 00:30:29.910
The goal is to get through that two weeks

749
00:30:29.910 --> 00:30:31.080
as easy as possible.

750
00:30:31.080 --> 00:30:34.320
It is a risk factor for postpartum depression, though.

751
00:30:34.320 --> 00:30:36.570
Postpartum depression is really clinically defined

752
00:30:36.570 --> 00:30:39.633
as any depression that occurs within a year of delivery.

753
00:30:40.710 --> 00:30:42.510
Research-wise, it's about three months

754
00:30:42.510 --> 00:30:43.590
is the window we look at.

755
00:30:43.590 --> 00:30:46.410
Again, it's that 15% prevalence.

756
00:30:46.410 --> 00:30:48.990
Depression comes across as a very anxious depression

757
00:30:48.990 --> 00:30:51.660
with a lot of overactivity.

758
00:30:51.660 --> 00:30:54.300
And they have thoughts of harming the infant,

759
00:30:54.300 --> 00:30:56.550
not stabbing the infant or killing the infant,

760
00:30:56.550 --> 00:30:58.230
but doing something wrong

761
00:30:58.230 --> 00:31:00.597
and the infant being harmed as a consequence of that.

762
00:31:00.597 --> 00:31:04.950
And there's multiple psychological, socioeconomic issues

763
00:31:04.950 --> 00:31:06.120
as well as biological.

764
00:31:06.120 --> 00:31:07.920
And the biggest biological risk factor

765
00:31:07.920 --> 00:31:11.460
for postpartum depression is depression during pregnancy.

766
00:31:11.460 --> 00:31:12.750
So how do we address that?

767
00:31:12.750 --> 00:31:17.220
We treat a patient that is depressed during pregnancy

768
00:31:17.220 --> 00:31:18.660
for that depression.

769
00:31:18.660 --> 00:31:20.640
If it's mild, we use psychotherapy,

770
00:31:20.640 --> 00:31:22.440
if it's moderate to severe,

771
00:31:22.440 --> 00:31:25.620
we use psychopharmacology and/or therapy.

772
00:31:25.620 --> 00:31:27.977
If we use a therapy, we use some of the SSRIs

773
00:31:27.977 --> 00:31:31.440
and monotherapy is probably the best.

774
00:31:31.440 --> 00:31:33.780
Really important is lost in this slide,

775
00:31:33.780 --> 00:31:36.540
is that if we stop the antidepressant during pregnancy,

776
00:31:36.540 --> 00:31:39.660
they have five times the risk of relapsing going forward.

777
00:31:39.660 --> 00:31:41.940
And then there's a new antidepressant coming out

778
00:31:41.940 --> 00:31:43.740
that's indicated only for postpartum,

779
00:31:43.740 --> 00:31:46.290
it's a two week oral medication,

780
00:31:46.290 --> 00:31:48.396
it's $20,000 for the two week.

781
00:31:48.396 --> 00:31:52.293
They're limiting that to psychiatrists right now, surprise.

782
00:31:53.520 --> 00:31:56.430
Have any of you seen postpartum psychosis?

783
00:31:56.430 --> 00:31:58.230
Yeah, it's really scary, right?

784
00:31:58.230 --> 00:32:00.870
I mean, you round on the woman one day,

785
00:32:00.870 --> 00:32:02.190
you round on her the next day,

786
00:32:02.190 --> 00:32:03.720
and it's a completely different picture.

787
00:32:03.720 --> 00:32:06.510
She is psychotic, it happens like a lightning bolt,

788
00:32:06.510 --> 00:32:09.313
within 12 to 72 hours after delivery,

789
00:32:09.313 --> 00:32:11.340
they can get psychotic.

790
00:32:11.340 --> 00:32:12.240
If it's gonna happen,

791
00:32:12.240 --> 00:32:14.970
it's usually happened by about three to four months.

792
00:32:14.970 --> 00:32:17.402
They're very bizarre, very hypermotor.

793
00:32:17.402 --> 00:32:20.910
Bipolar disorder and a history of postpartum psychosis

794
00:32:20.910 --> 00:32:22.380
are the biggest risk factors.

795
00:32:22.380 --> 00:32:24.270
These are a true psychiatric emergency,

796
00:32:24.270 --> 00:32:28.350
these patients often require admission to a psychiatric unit

797
00:32:28.350 --> 00:32:31.380
for both their safety and the infant's safety.

798
00:32:31.380 --> 00:32:33.810
So in conclusion, the key points of the exam

799
00:32:33.810 --> 00:32:35.670
is pay attention to the screening,

800
00:32:35.670 --> 00:32:37.961
know the aspects of the treatment of depression,

801
00:32:37.961 --> 00:32:40.140
the importance of continuity treatment

802
00:32:40.140 --> 00:32:42.300
for those patients with three or more episodes,

803
00:32:42.300 --> 00:32:44.430
and know that the adequate trial for depression

804
00:32:44.430 --> 00:32:45.930
is about four to six weeks.

805
00:32:45.930 --> 00:32:48.690
Know that pregnancy is not protective

806
00:32:48.690 --> 00:32:51.840
as well as antidepressants are okay with lactation.

807
00:32:51.840 --> 00:32:53.310
And that's what I got so far.

808
00:32:53.310 --> 00:32:54.143
So, all right.

809
00:32:54.143 --> 00:32:56.220
<v Host>Thank you very much Dr. Heinrich.</v>

810
00:32:57.773 --> 00:33:00.356
(gentle music)

